            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1458970531,
            "creation_date": 1458968809,
            "body": "<p>Instead of Array you can use ArrayList. ArrayList is a Kind of Dynamic Array. it will grow automatically once the it reaches to the size. <\/p>\n\n<p>to use ArrayList do this. <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>static List&lt;String&gt; users = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\n\nprivate static void Update() {\n   users.add(inputUser)\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 36231840,
            "question_id": 36231799,
            "last_edit_date": 1458970531
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/9474H.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1219848,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1186689,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1186689/kdeogharkar",
                "reputation": 10949,
                "display_name": "KDeogharkar",
                "accept_rate": 80
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1458971278,
            "creation_date": 1458968697,
            "body": "<p>Use <em><a href=\"http://www.tutorialspoint.com/java/java_collections.htm\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Collections<\/a><\/em> instead. You can use ArrayList for an auto-growing array.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36231831,
            "question_id": 36231799,
            "last_edit_date": 1592644375
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-s3zWlFJo4U0/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAtw/43mJHVmtAyc/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
                "account_id": 7115792,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 5442142,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5442142/carlos-l%c3%a1zaro-costa",
                "reputation": 73,
                "display_name": "Carlos L&#225;zaro Costa"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1458970551,
            "creation_date": 1458970220,
            "body": "<p>As others said, you can use collections. In your case you're interested in dynamic lists, so you'll like <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/ArrayList.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">ArrayList<\/a> which uses arrays internally to grow. Specifically, doubles its size each time is full, to get an amortized constant time on addition methods.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Collection.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Collections<\/a> need to be imported from <code>java.util<\/code> package.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can use ArrayList in this way:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;(); // You've to add parentheses, because this is an initialization from the empty constructor of ArrayList class.\nlist.add(\"Some object of the generic type\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Since Java 7 you can instantiate generic classes with the diamond operator, which infers the types:<\/p>\n\n<p><code>List&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>Check Java API for more methods you can use.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36231945,
            "question_id": 36231799,
            "last_edit_date": 1458970551
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22f58c3efd6d4aa704e61b8034e5e65d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 8066262,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6080300,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6080300/kamal",
                "reputation": 84,
                "display_name": "kamal"
